To further verify the modification of NiO by CQDs, FTIR tests were conducted. In the FTIR spectrum of pure NiO (blue curve in Fig. S1a), there was a strong peak at 643 cm−1, which might be due to the tensile vibration of Ni-O. In the FTIR spectrum of pure CQDs, there was an obvious peak at 1632 cm-1, which could be ascribed to C = C or C = N vibration, and a wide peak at 2200 might be due to vibration of C = C and C≡C (
                           Fig. S2
                        ). As shown in the FTIR spectrum of NiO@CQDs (red curve in Figure S1a), after the modification by CQDs, the peak at at 643 cm−1 might be due to the tensile vibration of Ni-O, the peak centered at 1632 cm−1 could be designed to C = C or C = N vibration, the peak located at 2356 cm−1 corresponded to C = O vibration, and the peak at 2218 cm−1 was associated with the vibration of C≡C, which might be caused by the incomplete decomposition of biomass carbon in the preparation of CQDs. [34–36].

Under the optimal test conditions, 0.5 µM, 5 µM and 10 µM standard Cu2+ solutions were added to deionized water, tap water and lake water, respectively, and the absorbance change at 450 nm of the system was tested (

                           Fig. S4

                        ). According to the linear relationship in Fig. 4
                        d, the Cu2+ concentration was calculated, and the recovery rate was 97.14% −112.50% compared with the added concentration (Table 1
                        ), which indicated that NiO@CQDs-3 had good performance in the detection of Cu2+ in actual water.
